post_text:
You’re invited to the public launch of a sweeping agenda to address racial disparities and systemic racism--especially anti-Black racism--in #LosAngeles. Join us tomorrow 9/9 at noon for the launch of “No Going Back,” a groundbreaking USC/UCLA report, which includes data and context about how COVID-19 lifted the veil of structural racism in LA, guiding principles to reinvent and reimagine a more equitable LA and a policy blueprint for system change. Committee for Greater L.A.
RSVP: http://bit.ly/nogoingbackla
Wednesday 9/9 at noon

post_text:
As of today, 40% of households in Los Angeles County have yet to respond to the #2020Census. This could mean a 40% budget cut to LA County for the next 10 years, that will adversely impact health and education programs for the youth. You can make a difference, says LACOE Census Outreach Specialist Esmeralda Flores, by participating in the countywide Census Chalkathon. Grab some chalk, get artistic and spread the word: #BeCounted!
#CaStudentsCount and #LACcensuschalkathon.

post_text:
Supt. Debra Duardo welcomes LA County students back to school: “We are excited to have you back....We want to make sure you have a voice in how your education is moving forward.” Dr. Duardo asks students to reach out to someone at their school if they need anything – from connectivity or devices to having someone to talk to about their feelings during this pandemic. “This is a time for innovation and making sure we’re improving and doing better, and that we’re meeting your needs.”
#welcomebacktoschool #BackToSchool2020 #LACOE

post_text:
JUST IN: Supt. Debra Duardo has launched an advisory council to bring the views of students into conversations & decision-making about public education. This council will involve 25 diverse high school students from districts countywide. They will engage in dialogue with Supt. Duardo on educational equity, the quality of public education, student well-being and other topics of concern, advising her on key issues facing youth.

Students are currently being recruited to apply to serve on the advisory council. The group will meet virtually on a quarterly basis beginning in Fall 2020. Interested students will need to complete an application and have a teacher, administrator or certificated school staff member submit a recommendation. They will also need to show they have the permission of their parent/guardian to participate.

Applications due 5 pm on Aug. 28. More info: https://bit.ly/3gbkh1n Please share widely!

SUMMER LEARNING TIP:
Turn off the TV, computer & video games or limit screen time and keep children moving with physical activities that also encourage learning. For example, organize a scavenger hunt that leads them around your backyard or a local playground or park. You can also use educational apps or games where kids must walk, run or jump to win or earn points.
More tips in our summer learning toolkit:
https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Ca2f2DErPSkH3EAXN3UiBaxIp4MXpIeM #LACOE

post_text: Today, we celebrate #Juneteenth that marks the end of slavery in the US. We take this day to honor the journey and achievement of African Americans. It's also a great day to cap off a week of victories for social justice. The Supreme Court ruled to protect the DACA program and prevent workplace discrimination based on sexual orientation. Our Board of Education, in a resolution, and Supt. Debra Duardo, in this video message, reaffirm LACOE’s commitment to equity and justice for our students, staff, parents and communities. #LACOE #LosAngeles

post_text: Tomorrow is #NationalCensusDayofAction and the start of Census Action Week. Join a community caravan near you and help spread the word: Take the #2020Census now! https://my2020census.gov #LACOE #LosAngeles
shared_text:
Esmeralda Xochitl Flores
June 16 at 3:04 PM ·

Our communities have been historically undercounted. Taking the Census can mean political representation and resources. It's a form of racial and social justice. We all deserve to been seen, to be heard, and to be counted! This is why I continue to do this work. Tomorrow, June 17th I will be joining the car caravan through Downtown/Central Long Beach to promote the Census Count. #CaStudentsCount # LBCounts2020 #WeCountLA LACOE Staff Long Beach Unified School District

post_text: Superintendent Debra Duardo will be joining the 26th Annual Latina Action Day tomorrow! #LAD2020
shared_text:
Hispanas Organized for Political Equality (HOPE)
June 10 at 4:24 PM ·

We're excited to announce that Los Angeles County Office of Education Superintendent Dr. Debra Duardo and Sacramento City Unified School District Superintendent Jorge A. Aguilar, will be joining us for DAY 2 of #LAD2020!

We can't wait to see how their expertise will help guide our discussion about the impact that COVID-19 has on educational inequities for English Learners and Latinas in our state, and how they are working to close the opportunity gap! Tune in tomorrow at 9:00 AM PST for Session 2 of our Latina Action Day Conference! #LAD2020

Register at bit.ly/virtuallad

post_text: Here's one way to help keep your child engaged during distance learning: create a dedicated learning space, separate from where they play to help limit distractions. Homeschool Activity Idea: Want a meaningful project to work on with your child where he or she can make a difference, use their voice and learn about civic engagement?

And win amazing prizes such as a content creation kit and an online shout-out from their favorite celebrity?

Our 2020 Census contest with USC Annenberg Innovation Lab’s Count The Nation starts NOW!

Students: Create and post memes, videos, graphics or a photo on any social media account. For your caption, answer the question, “Why is the census important to my family, my school and/or my community? (50 - 100 words)

Use hashtags #StandUpBeCounted, #2020Census and YOUR school’s SPECIFIC contest hashtag so we can find you if you win!

Find more info at www.countthenation.org/lacoe-contest

post_text: We join in the outpouring of grief over the loss of basketball legend Kobe Bryant, his daughter and his friends. We pay tribute to Kobe’s commitment to uplift our homeless youth in LA County, an advocacy close to our hearts. He was a role model for our student athletes, with his remarkable work ethic & passion for the game. He inspired at-promise youth to work hard and follow their dreams.

Our LACHSA students will perform at the Grammy's tonight! 40 Music Department students will perform “I Sing the Body Electric” featuring Camila Cabello, Gary Clark Jr., John Legend, Joshua Bell, Common, Misty Copeland, Lang Lang, Cyndi Lauper, Ben Platt and War and Treaty. LACHSA is a GRAMMY Museum Signature School and is honored to be part of this number honoring longtime Grammy producer, Ken Ehrlich. A big “thank you” to David Sears, the Grammy Museum and Ricky Minor for this incredible opportunity.
Watch this clip featuring LACHSA musicians selected to play at the 2020 Grammy Awards on CBS tonight!

post_text: Proud to recognize an outstanding educator!
shared_text:
Castaic High School
January 23 at 3:01 PM ·

“Remember to keep reading and writing dancing through your classrooms and invite students to be swept up so that they can harness their powers, find their voices, and make magic of their own” ~Castaic English Teacher, Sarah Avanessian.
Ms. Avanessian was honored today with the Beth Dalton Literacy Leadership Award from the LA County Office of Education at their Literacy Lifts Conference. She also presented to educators from all over LA County about teaching writing to students. Gifted with 1000 Scholastic dollars, Ms. Avanessian will share this honor with our Coyotes by filling her classroom library with even more Carpe Librum books. We are so proud of Ms. Avanessian and are lucky to have her teaching our Coyotes!! #yearoffirsts. William S. Hart Union High School District Los Angeles County Office of Education

post_text: Congrats to Compton Unified School District's McKinley Elementary & Burbank Unified School District's Joaquin Miller Elementary, William McKinley Elementary, Providencia Elementary & George Washington Elementary for winning the California Exemplary Arts Education Award! Thank you for leading the way in preparing our students to excel in the creative economy!
shared_text:
California Department of Education
January 7 at 4:21 PM ·

State Superintendent of Public Instruction Tony Thurmond today announced that 13 California elementary schools were selected for the California Exemplary Arts Education Award. Schools were eligible to apply based on instruction identified in the California Arts Standards for Public Schools (Arts Standards) and performance and progress on indicators on the California School Dashboard.

Read more: https://www.cde.ca.gov/nr/ne/yr20/yr20rel01.asp

post_text: Our Superintendent of Schools #DebraDuardo says the label “high school dropout” has followed her even after she got her doctorate from UCLA. It’s time to drop negative labeling of vulnerable youth and focus on their immense potential for success. #AB413 #AtPromise, NOT #AtRisk.
text: Our Superintendent of Schools #DebraDuardo says the label “high school dropout” has followed her even after she got her doctorate from UCLA. It’s time to drop negative labeling of vulnerable youth and focus on their immense potential for success. #AB413 #AtPromise, NOT #AtRisk.

post_text: Today we celebrated what our students represent—the promise of brighter futures. We're very proud to be a sponsor of AB 413 that changes "at-risk" to "at-promise" students in the Ed Code and Penal Code. It's an important first step in ensuring that we use uplifting words to describe our vulnerable children and focus on their potential for success. Thank you, Assemblymember Reggie Jones-Sawyer and Senator Steven Bradford for leading this initiative in Sacramento! #WordsMatter
text: Today we celebrated what our students represent—the promise of brighter futures. We're very proud to be a sponsor of AB 413 that changes "at-risk" to "at-promise" students in the Ed Code and Penal Code. It's an important first step in ensuring that we use uplifting words to describe our vulnerable children and focus on their potential for success. Thank you, Assemblymember Reggie Jones-Sawyer and Senator Steven Bradford for leading this initiative in Sacramento! #WordsMatter

post_text: As a former high school dropout and teen mom, our County Superintendent of Schools Dr. Debra Duardo knows how promoting students’ social-emotional health can change lives. Today she joined community partners in launching countywide WELL-BEING CENTERS at Torres HS in East LA.
text: As a former high school dropout and teen mom, our County Superintendent of Schools Dr. Debra Duardo knows how promoting students’ social-emotional health can change lives. Today she joined community partners in launching countywide WELL-BEING CENTERS at Torres HS in East LA.

post_text: Our youth’s #wellbeing is so important for them to achieve success and live happy and fulfilling lives. Today we’re so excited to join our community partners in launching countywide WELL-BEING CENTERS at Torres HS in East LA. The first of its kind, the centers will work with teachers, parents & administrators to promote the social-emotional health & academic success of every student.

post_text: Opening the #2020Census Curriculum Training and launch of #LACOE's Count Me In! outreach project today, civil rights leader Thomas Saenz thanks educators and students for helping ensure that everyone is counted in the upcoming census. Saenz, #MALDEF president and general counsel, led successful efforts to block a citizenship question on the 2020 census, which was meant to “trigger a massive undercount in immigrant communities.” #CountMeIn #CuentaConMigo #CountOnUs #CaliforniaForAll #BeCounted!

post_text: Joined with county officials to announce dramatic expansion of a school violence prevention program in the wake of recent mass shootings and in time for back-to-school season.
text: Joined with county officials to announce dramatic expansion of a school violence prevention program in the wake of recent mass shootings and in time for back-to-school season.

post_text:
Supt. Debra Duardo joined with county officials today to announce expansion of the START school violence prevention program in the wake of recent mass shootings and in time for the back-to-school season.

“Our priority as educators is to ensure all children have the safe learning environments they deserve,” Duardo said. “While schools remain among the safest places in our communities, START gives us a vital tool for preventing acts of targeted violence that sadly are on the rise around the nation.”

post_text:
The 2019 California Assessment Conference is a unique opportunity for classroom educators to explore connections between assessments and classroom instruction, and learn how to use assessment tools and resources to support teaching and learning.

This conference has been designed to create collaboration among educators who wish to discover how others are integrating all components of the state assessment system.

A variety of sessions and key topics, covered over two and a half days, allow for a customized learning experience while minimizing time away from the classroom. Participants will learn, explore, find inspiration and return to the classroom ready to apply new skills and knowledge.

We look forward to seeing you in Oakland on October 16–18, 2019.

Get info and register here: https://www.cdecac.org/
